<?xml version='1.0' encoding='utf-8'?>  
<chapter xml:id="CHAPTERFTC" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Integration in Its Simplest Forms  </title>

<introduction>
<figure  xml:id="FIGURE">
<caption>
<url href="https://www.frankandernest.com" visual="https://www.frankandernest.com">Frank and Ernest</url>
</caption>
<image source="IC/FredGinger.png" width="80%">
<shortdescription></shortdescription>
</image>
</figure>
<p>
If asked for a one sentence description of Integral Calculus, most mathematicians will say something like, <q>It is the opposite of Differential Calculus,</q> or, <q>It is Differential Calculus run backwards.</q> 
</p>
<p>
While, not inaccurate, this characterization is woefully inadequate. 
</p>
<p>
Integration is a much deeper, and more complex subject, as the
following chapters will show. In it<rsq/>s more
advanced forms integration is more like
differentiationg backwards, in heels, blindfolded, carrying a large
weight, while being shot at with poisonous darts. 
</p>
<p>
But in it<rsq/>s simplest forms it is helpful to remember that it
really is just <q>integration run backwards.</q> 
</p>

    <!-- <title>A Quick Review of Differential Calculus</title> -->
